### 2. `docs/design-anti-patterns.md` — Amend AP-066

Find the `<a id="ap-066"></a>` section and replace its body with:

```markdown
<a id="ap-066"></a>
## AP-066: Unconstrained Flex Compression Breaking Identity Text

**Status: ACTIVE** — Amended FB-146 (added identity-chrome priority rule and three-property shield).

**Trigger:** A nav logo or site wordmark wraps to two lines, shrinks, or disappears when the browser window is squeezed. Usually happens when `white-space: nowrap` is placed only on a child `<span>` rather than on the flex container itself, or when `min-width: max-content` is absent.

**Why it's wrong:** Site identity (logo, wordmark, name) is not a soft element. It is the foundational identity line of the page. The flex algorithm treats every item as negotiable unless explicitly told otherwise — and `flex-shrink: 0` alone is not enough if `flex-basis: auto` resolves to a value the browser considers compressible. The logo wrapping to two lines communicates brokenness and undermines the brand's precision identity (see `docs/design/branding.md`).

**The Identity-Chrome Priority Rule (codified here):**
> **Identity chrome (logo, wordmark, site name) must never yield to viewport pressure at any width. Every pixel of compression must be absorbed by the surrounding chrome — nav links, taglines, secondary text — not by the identity element.**
>
> This is not a responsive design choice. It is a hard invariant. The tagline CAN wrap to two lines. The personal identity blurb CAN wrap. The logo CANNOT.

**Why partial fixes fail:**
| What was tried | Why it fails |
|---|---|
| `white-space: nowrap` on child `<span>` only | The flex container's intrinsic size is still negotiable; browser can narrow the `inline-flex` box even if its child can't internally wrap |
| `flex-shrink: 0` without `min-width: max-content` | `flex-shrink: 0` operates relative to `flex-basis`; if `flex-basis: auto` resolves to a narrow computed width, shrink: 0 locks in that narrow value |
| `min-width: 0` on the soft side without `overflow: hidden` | The soft container can still resist compression if any child has a large intrinsic minimum width; the logo then gets squeezed instead |

**Correct alternative — three-property shield, ALL on the container element itself:**
```scss
.logo {
  display: inline-flex;
  align-items: center;
  flex-shrink: 0;           // 1. does not yield to flex pressure
  white-space: nowrap;      // 2. on the container, not just a child span
  min-width: max-content;   // 3. base size = natural rendered width; flex-shrink: 0 locks it there
}
```

**Soft-side counterpart — BOTH properties required:**
```scss
.links {
  min-width: 0;       // allows flex children to shrink below intrinsic width
  overflow: hidden;   // seals off the soft side; prevents it from forcing the row wider
}
```

**Belt-and-suspenders (redundant but harmless):** also add `white-space: nowrap` on the child text `<span>` — it costs nothing and provides a second layer of protection if the container rule ever gets removed.

**Applied in:** `src/components/ui/Navigation/Navigation.module.scss` (`.logo`, `.links`, `.tagline`)

**See:** FB-146

**Frustration caused:** 1 round — logo wordmark collapsed to two lines under squeeze at any viewport narrower than ~520px.
```

